<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Pearson beats forecasts with Pounds 151m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PEARSON, the publishing, banking and industrial group which owns the
Financial Times, announced pre-tax profits of Pounds 150.8m for 1992, a fall
of 16 per cent, but significantly better than forecasts which ranged as low
as Pounds 134m.
The result, coupled with a proposed increase in the final dividend to 6.625p
(6.25p) for a total of 12p (11.625p), boosted the Pearson share price which
closed up 27p at 404p. Earnings per share were 19.3p (24.7p).
Lord Blakenham, chairman and chief executive, said that despite lower
profits the company was starting to see benefits from a cost reduction
programme which had included some 3,000 redundancies in just over two years.
'We generated more cash than ever before, and held or increased our share of
sales in many of our markets,' he said.
Reporting under the new FRS 3 accounting standard, the 1991 pre-tax profit
of Pounds 179.6m was boosted by a Pounds 33.2m gain on the sale of an
associate. Interest payable fell to Pounds 13.6m (Pounds 19.6m).
Operating profit from continuing operations, at Pounds 155.6m, was down 8
per cent. The main reason was the collapse in profits of oil services from
Pounds 34.7m to Pounds 500,000 on turnover down from Pounds 318.7m to Pounds
289.8m.
Mr David Veit, chief executive of the division, blamed a fall in gas prices
and drilling activity. A total of Dollars 20m (Pounds 14m) was spent on
redundancies and closures, and capital expenditure was cut from Dollars 42m
to Dollars 24m. The division has been profitable so far this year.
Books were 'the star performer', with operating profit up 35 per cent to
Pounds 80.4m. Penguin profits doubled to Pounds 26.3m on record sales and
had eight titles in the January best sellers list in the New York Times.
The Financial Times group increased profits by 5 per cent to Pounds 18.5m
including contributions from foreign newspapers such as Les Echos but
excluding associate companies. The newspapers division overall made Pounds
31.1m, a 5 per cent improvement.
Mr Frank Barlow, Pearson's chief operating officer, said that BSkyB was now
making operating profits of more than Pounds 1m a week. The first return in
the form of interest on loan stock was expected this year.
Investment banking showed a 9 per cent fall, with an operating profit of
Pounds 23.7m. Profits from fine china fell by 39 per cent to Pounds 10.7m.
Lord Blakenham said Pearson was now 'potentially very profitable' following
cost-cutting and savings.
Mr Guy Lamming, a James Capel media analyst, yesterday described the results
as 'mixed' with better-than-expected performances from books and banking.
'There is the feeling that they have scraped the bottom and things are
looking up for the company,' he said, increasing his 1993 pre-tax forecast
from Pounds 170m to Pounds 179m.
</TEXT>
