<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / UK Company News: BCSR directors frustrate move for
restructuring of board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHAREHOLDER move to restructure the board of Bristol Channel Ship
Repairers has been frustrated by a boardroom coup.
Shareholders attending an extraordinary meeting called at the request of the
company's biggest shareholder, Andreas Ugland, the private Norwegian
shipping group, backed resolutions which would have wrestled boardroom
control away from Mr Christopher Bailey, the current chairman, and three of
his associates.
Ugland built up a 24.19 per cent stake in Bristol Channel through its UK
subsidiary, acquiring the bulk of its stake in July when it bought 18m
shares from CH Bailey, which also operates dry dock facilities in the
Bristol Channel.
This cut Bailey's holding to 8.21 per cent. Three Ugland directors joined
the board but since then the two sides have conducted an increasingly
acrimonious debate over the management, financial performance and prospects
of the company, which owns five docks in South Wales.
This led to the move by Ugland to remove three Bristol Channel directors, Mr
James Garvin, Mr Michael David and Mr Lionel Dotchon, and appoint Viscount
Tenby to a new five member board. These resolutions were passed at the EGM
held on Friday.
However, Mr Bailey convened a directors' meeting the day before the EGM and
24 hours after the closing time for proxies.
At the meeting, attended by the three directors under attack, four
previously undisclosed additional non-executive directors were appointed
together with Viscount Tenby. The four are Sir Robin Maxwell-Hyslop, Mr
Kenneth Griffin, Mr Thomas Bishop and Mr Robert Scammell.
In addition, one of the removed directors, Mr David, was appointed general
manager of the ship repair yard.
In a statement issued after the action Ugland claimed that 'the manner and
circumstances in which the new directors were appointed is wholly
unacceptable.
'The shareholders' intentions and wishes as carried at the EGM have been
frustrated by a clear abuse of Director's fiduciary duties and powers'.
Mr John Love, one of the three Ugland directors on the board, said Ugland
was 'reviewing the situation'.
No-one from CH Bailey was available for comment yesterday. Mr Bailey was
said to be 'out of the country.'
Last month BCSR reported a Pounds 236,261 loss for the 28 weeks to October
9, against a profit of Pounds 74,884. The loss, on turnover of just Pounds
34,192 (Pounds 661,801), included a Pounds 150,000 non-recurring item 'for
cancelling and amending management agreements with CH Bailey'.
</TEXT>
