<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Inchcape rises 28% to Pounds 250m on sales growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACQUISITIONS and strong organic growth helped Inchcape, the UK-based motor
and business services group, increase annual pre-tax profits by 28 per cent
to Pounds 250m.
Sales rose 39 per cent to Pounds 5.04bn in the year to December 31, boosted
by a 10-month contribution from Tozer Kemsley and Millbourn, the motor
trader it bought for Pounds 383m.
Although TKM contributed Pounds 48.3m to total operating profits of Pounds
293m, Inchcape said its underlying businesses showed organic profits growth
of 10 per cent.
Sir David Plastow, chairman, said: 'Generally around the world the economic
environment in 1992 was tough but despite this, the group was able to
produce good results. Many of Inchcape's businesses are in those economies
which have grown well during the year, while in weaker markets most of our
operations have still managed to succeed.'
Earnings per share rose 3.7 per cent to 31p. Sir David said the benefit the
group gained from Budget changes in advance corporation tax had been one of
the factors behind the decision to raise the final dividend to 8.35p (from
7p), giving a total of 13.75p (up from 11.75p), an increase of 17 per cent.
As well as adopting the new FRS 3 accounting standard, Inchcape calculated
'normalised' pre-tax profits and earnings, excluding items which had been
accounted as extraordinary under the old standard.
Under these figures, including gains on disposals of properties and
investments, earnings per share rose 18 per cent to 31.6p and pre-tax
profits by 36 per cent to Pounds 252m.
Sir David said: 'The motors business grew strongly, quite apart from the
added impetus of the acquisition of TKM. All of our franchises in Hong Kong
had an outstanding year. Toyota (GB) also enjoyed a good year and will
benefit increasingly in 1993 from the newly-opened Toyota manufacturing
plant at Burnaston.'
The marketing business side improved profits, due mainly to the Pounds 32m
acquisition of Spinneys, a group of marketing and retail companies. Fastest
growth was in the Middle East, organically as well as by acquisition, with
good results from South America, Singapore and Thailand.
In the service business stream, shipping greatly increased its turnover, but
profits fell mainly because of lower Japanese activity. Insurance offset the
lower reinsurance market with solid growth by Bain Clarkson's core UK retail
business.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
