FT  30 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Embarrassment television moves a step further down the line today with the
screening of a quiz show in which, we are assured, the competitors are all
homeless, the winner gets a 'dream house', and the losers are left to the
mercy of the streets. But don't worry; the spoof is all in a good cause.
Channel 4 is presenting Come On Down And Out (8.00) as part of its 'Gimme
Shelter' season which is focusing on homelessness. ITV's pilots for possible
new comedy series in 'Comedy Playhouse' have mostly been distressingly bad.
Today's programme, Cut And Run (8.30) is about a video company asked to film
badgers as part of a campaign to prevent development of a golf course. I was
becoming disillusioned about Philip Larkin after all the recent nasty
revelations, but if his poetry infuriates Professor Terry Eagleton he cannot
be all bad. Eagleton wades into Larkin in the latest of the 'J'accuse'
series on Without Walls (9.00 C4). The second half of this nearly always
interesting culture magazine is, again, presented by Camille Paglia, the
American controversialist, who explores 'The Lolita Syndrome'.
