FT  30 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tebbit warns City over Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BIGGEST danger to the City is not Britain refusing to ratify Maastricht,
but Britain ratifying the treaty and losing business to other financial
centres, Lord Tebbit, the arch Euro-sceptic and former Tory chairman, argued
yesterday.
He attacked as a 'silly myth' the claim that Maastricht would lead to the
City losing business to Frankfurt. 'The danger is that we may ratify and
lose our business to New York, Tokyo, Hong Kong, Singapore and before long
Shanghai,' he said.
'Did anyone predict the loss of business to France had their referendum vote
been 51 per cent to 49 per cent instead of 49 per cent to 51 per cent
against the treaty?' he asked.
If Britain rejected the treaty, 'then our position within the European
Community will remain precisely the same as it is today - under the Treaty
of Rome as amended by the Single European Act, warts and all,' Lord Tebbit
said.
He said angrily: 'I am not impressed by the pro-Maastricht arguments of
those pillars of the City establishment whose banks have lost billions of
shareholders' money by bad business decisions when they write to The Times
to say that I do not know my business as a politician.
To them I say as a shareholder, 'a period of reticence might be welcomed'.'
</TEXT>
