<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: The one-man English Development
Agency - The rising influence of Lord Walker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUGH retired from politics, Lord Walker, the former cabinet minister
appointed to co-ordinate measures to help the communities affected by pit
closures, wields more influence than some still in government.
His remit has expanded almost imperceptibly to include advising Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, on the broader implications for
regional policy and for inward investment measures. Before the election, he
was appointed chairman-designate of the urban regeneration agency, also by
Mr Heseltine, who was his junior minister at environment in the early 1970s.
The two share a conviction that government should work in partnership with
industry. Some Whitehall officials believe that in Lord Walker, Mr Heseltine
has realised an ambition thwarted by some of his colleagues and found a
one-man English Development Agency in all but name.
But so far, Lord Walker's mission has been somewhat hanging fire. The URA
will not begin its work until the autumn, and the coalfields project has
been held up while the government reviewed its endorsement of British Coal's
decision to close 31 pits. The white paper should, however, mark a watershed
in terms of making progress.
Lord Walker said yesterday that while the delays had been 'frustrating', the
time had been usefully spent in meetings which brought home to officials the
need to ensure that their activities dovetailed. Measures were now ready to
be activated 'immediately' a decision had been reached on a particular pit.
Though the great affection he expresses for the coal industry is not
universally reciprocated by those who remember him as energy secretary at
the time of the bitter 1984-85 miners' strike, some of the areas which feel
most at risk have invited him to visit, and he has been to Durham, Yorkshire
and Nottinghamshire.
'You have to have a team,' he says of the need to get local councils,
industry, training and enterprise councils, and government working together.
One of his biggest fans at Westminster says, however, that it is his
'bullying manner', which makes him ideal for the job.
While Labour admits he has abilities as a 'super-salesman', opposition MPs
are more doubtful about what they see as his belief that simply by insisting
a venture is a success it can be turned into one. A few express more serious
reservations as well: last week some Labour MPs tabled Commons motions
accusing him of misleading MPs about discussions on private sector
involvement in the Welsh Development Agency.
</TEXT>
