<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: MoD revives Pounds 170m helicopter
carrier plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday threw a lifeline to Swan Hunter, the Tyneside
shipyard, by reviving plans for a specialised naval helicopter carrier,
expected to cost about Pounds 170m.
The carrier emerged as a prime candidate for cancellation earlier this year
in order to help the Ministry of Defence meet the budget cuts imposed in
last November's public expenditure settlement.
After intensive lobbying by naval chiefs and by Swan Hunter, Mr Jonathan
Aitken, defence procurement minister, said yesterday in a written
parliamentary answer that the MoD was keeping the carrier in its programme
and expected to place an order later this year.
However, he said tenderers had been asked to 'clarify' their bids. He also
warned that the ministry would apply 'normal technical and value-for-money
criteria' in deciding the contract award.
Swan Hunter, which has no naval shipbuilding work on its books beyond next
year, is relying heavily on the order to maintain its 2,200 jobs. But it
will have to compete against the VSEL yard at Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria,
which envisages buying the hull from the Norwegian-owned Kvaerner Govan
commercial shipyard on Clydeside. Both bids were submitted last October.
Mr Alex Marsh, joint group chief executive of Swan Hunter, the Tyneside
shipbuilder, said it was excellent news, both for the Royal Navy and Swan
Hunter.
Swan Hunter now faces a bitter fight for the order, worth around Pounds
170m, from VSEL, which has linked with Govan on the Clyde to tender for the
landing platform helicopter.
'Quite clearly we intend to win this competition,' said Mr Marsh. 'We'll win
it by taking advantage of our excellent track record in building ships of
this type.'
Mr Marsh has described the order as 'absolutely critical' for Swan Hunter,
which has a blank order book after 1994. The company, which employs 2,200,
has spent Pounds 1.5m on its bid.
The decision means that the MoD will have to make cuts elsewhere in its
equipment programme.
</TEXT>
