<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Council tendering rules to be
altered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPULSORY competitive tendering of county council and district council
services will be suspended immediately before reorganisations arising from
recommendations of the Local Government Commission, Mr Robin Squire,
environment minister, said yesterday.
He said the requirement to put services out to tender would be suspended for
local authorities after parliament approved legislation to merge or
reorganise them. New authorities would be required to start tendering as
soon as possible after their setting-up, with new contracts operative no
more than 18 months later.
However, the government also announced that tendering will be extended to
local authority construction-related and corporate services from 1995-96.
It also announced new regulations to stop anti-competitive behaviour by
local authorities which helps the in-house workforce to win contracts. These
include stricter rules to separate the responsibilities of those putting out
work to tender from the council workforce.
The timetable is also to be altered for contracts worth more than Pounds
100,000 or lasting more than one year to provide extra time for contractors
to draw up bids. The new rules come into force on 10 May.
</TEXT>
<XX>
