<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Cook accuses Heseltine of
misleading Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NONE OF the 12 pits saved by the coal white paper will be open in a year, Mr
Robin Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary, said yesterday,
accusing Mr Michael Heseltine of trying to mislead wavering Conservative
backbenchers.
In last night's debate, in which the government secured a majority of 22, Mr
Cook said the trade and industry secretary had selected a number of pits for
reprieve purely to get rebel backbenchers 'in the same lobby as himself'
without securing markets for 'one extra bag of coal'.
He added that what the government was doing was ' . . digging a pit for them
to fall into because one year from now, not one of these pits will be open'.
He said the 'biggest failure' of the white paper was that it had not
accepted any of the trade and industry select committee's recommendations
for ending the 'rigged' electricity market.
He challenged Mr Heseltine to explain where the market for the 13m tonnes
the 12 pits would produce this year would come from, arguing that the coal
imports which this production might displace had only been forecast at 9m
tonnes and contracts for 2m tonnes of this had already been signed.
Faced by Conservative demands to say whether he backed strikes threatened by
miners, Mr Cook said the Union of Democratic Mineworkers' ballot on possible
action highlighted the extent of the government 'betrayal'.
In his opening speech Mr Heseltine said no pit would be closed without the
private sector having an opportunity to bid for it and set out fresh details
of the circumstances under which subsidies might be offered to private mine
operators.
He said he would be prepared to offer a subsidy to private-sector
organisations which could demonstrate they had found a 'genuinely'
additional market for coal. This would exclude offers to supply coal under
the core five-year contracts signed yesterday.
He rejected suggestions that the tapering subsidies announced last week
would be for two years only. The trade and industry secretary indicated they
would last until the industry was privatised.
Mrs Elizabeth Peacock, who voted against the government, said she could not
support the government motion because it did not address 'the problem of
equality in the market'.
She said coal needed 'a fair crack at an equal-opportunity market'.
Privatisation ought to get rid of layers of British Coal bureaucracy such as
its regional offices 'and hopefully the chairman as well'.
Mr Richard Alexander, Conservative MP for Newark, who also voted against the
government, said that the government had not done all it 'could or should
have done to provide a wider market for coal'. Coal privatisation should
have taken place before electricity privatisation, he said.
Mr Winston Churchill, who abstained on the motion, had earlier said he would
not support the government unless it indicated that it was prepared to
impose tighter restrictions on output from gas-powered electricity
generators.
He said the deal giving Electricite de France 'privileged' access to the UK
electricity market was 'a scandal of enormous proportions'.
Mr Richard Caborn, Labour chairman of the trade and industry committee,
protested that the core recommendations of his committee had been rejected
by Mr Heseltine, 'without exception'.
Winding up, Mr David Hunt, Welsh secretary, said the government was
optimistic of obtaining EC approval for its subsidy plans.
</TEXT>
