<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / InterCity bids for Pounds 150m to lease trains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL'S InterCity business yesterday said it hoped to take advantage
of the government's new rolling-stock leasing arrangements by bidding for
Pounds 150m of funds to finance a fleet of replacement trains for the London
Euston to Manchester line.
It also said it expected to report a small profit in the financial year just
ending and announced a marketing venture with Shell UK offering motorists
free train tickets in exchange for petrol vouchers.
The leasing deal would take advantage of the government's decision last
autumn to make Pounds 150m available to BR in an attempt to establish a
leasing market for rolling stock in the run-up to railway privatisation.
If it succeeds, InterCity will order about 15 more of the InterCity 225
trains built by GEC Alsthom, the Anglo-French engineering company. It has
already supplied trains for services running to and from London King's
Cross.
The 15 trains would replace those operating between London and Manchester,
and the displaced trains would in turn replace the outdated trains running
between London and the west Midlands.
However, InterCity's bid is subject to competition from Network SouthEast,
which wants to use the Pounds 150m to lease a fleet of 40 modified Networker
trains built by ABB Transportation (formerly Brel). These would replace
outdated rolling stock on Kent coast routes.
Mr Roger Freeman, minister for public transport, is expected to announce a
decision on the competing bids after Easter.
The joint promotion with Shell is the most unusual element of a spring
marketing campaign unveiled by Mr Chris Green, InterCity's managing
director.
Shell said it expected most tickets handed out to be for journeys that would
not otherwise have been undertaken, or at least not by road.
Other features of the InterCity marketing campaign, which is aimed at
countering the effects of the recession, include:
Afternoon tea and weekend restaurant car services will be restored on
selected services in response to passenger demand.
The InterCity shuttle will offer high-frequency services from London to the
west Midlands, east Midlands and East Anglia.
Tickets which are the cheapest in real terms since 1948 will be available
through the extension of Apex fares to all InterCity journeys of more than
150 miles.
</TEXT>
