<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Secretaries are 'undervalued'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE JOBS of secretaries and their bosses could become indistinguishable,
except in two important respects - pay and training, says the Industrial
Society.
A survey to be published by the society next month shows that secretaries in
Britain are increasingly taking on supervision of other staff and carrying
out research work. At the same time, bosses are increasingly doing their own
typing and making coffee.
The society said it was concerned that some organisations were 'playing a
confidence trick' on secretaries by not providing them with training for
their new responsibilities. Some companies were guilty of double standards
by providing training only for managers.
It said it was 'a logical next step, if companies expect more and more
management tasks to be performed by secretaries, that they must accept that
those secretaries are currently undervalued in pay terms'.
More than half of the nearly 400 managers surveyed claimed that their
companies were prepared to promote secretaries to managerial positions.
The managers were asked which jobs they thought would take more of
secretaries' time in future. The results included: setting up new systems
(52 per cent of those surveyed); own project work (45 per cent); research
(39 per cent); organising conferences, exhibitions and annual general
meetings (26 per cent); dealing with personnel matters (25 per cent).
The findings reinforce an Industrial Society survey carried out last month
which revealed that up to one third of a manager's working week is spent on
paperwork and that a declining number of bosses now have personal
secretaries.
</TEXT>
