<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Pounds 150m plan for opera house at risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AMBITIOUS Pounds 150m development plan for the Royal Opera House site in
London's Covent Garden could face a setback tonight when a Westminster City
Council committee is expected to seek assurances that sufficient money will
be available to complete the whole project.
The council, which gave planning permission for the four-phase plan in 1990,
still accepts the merits of the redevelopment in principle, but is against
piecemeal expansion. It is not convinced the opera house has sufficient
funds to complete the project.
A recommendation before the planning committee proposes acceptance of the
second phase of the development, which is for a seven-storey building to
include shops and a permanent home for the Royal Ballet, but only if certain
assurances are given.
The main assurance is confirmation that funding can be guaranteed for the
complete project. If this is not forthcoming, the committee will demand a
new design for the second phase that will be judged on its own merits rather
than as part of a larger development.
Acceptance of the committee's recommendations could delay the redevelopment
plans substantially as the opera house's management seeks more funding.
The redevelopment total of Pounds 150m is to be composed of Pounds 60m from
commercial development of the site and additional retail opportunities, with
the remaining Pounds 90m coming equally from public and private sources. The
management remains confident that the money will be raised, but it is not
yet clear where it will come from. The government has stated categorically
that no further Treasury money will be made available, and the most likely
source of public money is likely to be the national lottery's millennium
fund when it is launched next year.
Lord Sainsbury, a former chairman of the opera house and a likely private
benefactor, is to see Mr John Major, the prime minister, shortly to advocate
the merits of the development scheme and to seek Pounds 45m from the
millennium fund in three annual tranches.
</TEXT>
