<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Old wounds re-opened in the fight for funds: Mortgage
interest rates may have to rise again soon unless the battle between
building societies and the government for investors' funds is resolved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST signs of the next dispute between building societies and the
government over mortgage rates have started to emerge. Societies are warning
again that mortgage rates may rise unless the government makes National
Savings products less attractive to investors.
Mr Andrew Longhurst, chief executive of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, led last
year's assault on the government that culminated in the temporary withdrawal
of the National Savings First Option bond. Yesterday Mr Longhurst was going
over some familiar territory again.
He said; 'It would only take one major lender to move rates upwards and
everybody would shift. That would be another competitive pressure on
societies, and we are already squeezed.' However, like other chief
executives, Mr Longhurst thinks the battle is likely to be delayed for a few
months.
The first warning that tensions were about to rise emerged in the Budget
when Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, emphasised the role that National
Savings would have to play in funding the estimated Pounds 50bn public
sector deficit for 1993-94.
This role was not calculated to reassure societies, which are already
struggling to attract funds. Their net inflow of funds last year was only
Pounds 295m, compared to Pounds 5.8bn in 1991. Base interest rate falls have
made their savings products less attractive.
For the moment, the lack of attractiveness does not matter too much because
demand for mortgages is also low. However, any strong upturn in housing
demand could create problems for societies since they will lack the retail
funding from individual savers to satisfy it. The only way of getting such
retail funds would be to raise interest rates.
Mr Longhurst has no doubts that mortgage rates would have to rise to support
any retail savings rises. He said: 'Retail funds form the basis of our
business. They dictate our mortgage rates.' He added that societies would
have to attract new funds if they were to help any housing market revival.
There are two obstacles to getting retail funds. First, the re-emergence of
the First Option bond, now offering 6.34 per cent gross on investments of
more than Pounds 1,000. Second, limits on holdings of other National Savings
products have been raised.  This includes a five-fold rise in the income
bond limit to Pounds 250,000.
National Savings products took in a net Pounds 4.1bn in the 11 months to
February, compared with Pounds 2.6bn for the same period to February last
year. Treasury officials expect National Savings to contribute between
Pounds 4bn and Pounds 4.5bn to finance of the Pounds 50bn deficit in the
coming financial year.
The government has as yet shown few signs of discovering new sources of
deficit funding. It has not responded to calls from banks for new short-term
gilts to attract their funds. This means the government will be under more
pressure this year not to back down over National Savings.
There is one short-term alternative for societies: raising their wholesale
funds from capital markets. But the paucity of retail funds in the last year
means societies have limited capacity before they go over the limits on
holdings of wholesale funds set by the Building Societies Commission. The
limits average about 30 per cent of assets.
Halifax, the largest society, argues that it has plenty of capacity because
it was only at 15.2 per cent wholesale funding at the end of January. But
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester is at 25 per cent, and could bring in only Pounds
800m by raising its wholesale funds a further five percentage points.
A substantial rise in mortgage demand could therefore bring uncomfortable
funding pressure to bear later this year. Mr Adrian Coles, external affairs
manager of the Building Societies Association, said: 'If the housing market
does recover, it would obviously put some societies under strain.'
For now, societies can bear the strain. Mr Jim Birrell, Halifax chief
executive, said: 'We do not have a funding problem, but we might be forced
to seek alternatives if the mortgage market picks up fast.'
All this means that the battle between the government and mortgage lenders
is likely to be delayed until later this year, but is unlikely to be avoided
altogether. When it comes, the growing deficit means there will be less
chance of the government giving in to societies' complaints.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
