<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Community care guidelines attacked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITY social services directors yesterday attacked guidelines
issued by the government for its care-in-the-community proposals.
The proposals, which are due to be implemented on Thursday, will give local
authorities a leading role in assessing needs and arranging care for the
elderly, disabled and mentally ill.
The directors said guidance on measuring the care needs was 'unrealistic'
and should be more precise. The Association of Directors of Social Services
is seeking discussions with the Department of Health and local authority
associations to clarify the guidance.
Fears about the reforms' funding have been fuelled by a government circular,
which has been interpreted as advising councils not to tell people what
their needs are, in case they cannot be met.
A second circular - intended to allay local authority fears - predicted that
town halls would face legal challenges from people dissatisfied with
community care.
It has also emerged that ministers have no plans to collate evidence of
needs that are not met - leaving the government without a way to check the
effectiveness of community care.
A survey published yesterday said social services staff assessing the
community care requirements of disabled people were failing to report needs
they considered too expensive or difficult to fulfil.
The report, based on interviews with 50 disabled people and conducted by the
poverty research group The Joseph Rowntree Foundation, studies community
care practices in two unidentified local authority areas.
</TEXT>
