<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Lift-truck sales show 25% boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALES OF lift trucks and other warehouse equipment have risen by 25 per cent
year-on-year in the last four months, raising hopes that the three-year
recession in the UK materials handling industry is over.
The British Industrial Truck Association said that some 5,000 units were
sold in the four months from November to February.
Warehousing equipment sales have been particularly strong in the food
industry because of the trend towards third-party distribution. But even the
counterbalanced trucks used widely in manufacturing industry saw sales rise
by 15 per cent to 20 per cent.
Mr Graham Lovatt, vice-president for marketing at Hyster Europe and a senior
official in the truck association, said yesterday that the sector's UK sales
rose 1 per cent to 2 per cent last year to 15,000 units, compared with an
overall fall of 10 per cent for Europe.
Even so, the UK market is still a long way short of its 1988 peak of 25,000
units. Mr Tony de Mesquita, the association's president and director for
external affairs at Lansing-Linde, said there was a 'massive' oversupply of
equipment, and margins were negligible because of price discounting.
The lift-truck industry is cautious about predicting an end of the recession
because of recent 'false dawns' but the upturn over the four months to
February does appear to mirror a rise in confidence generally among the
industry's customers.
Mr Mesquita said domestic conditions, notably the UK's low inflation rate
and interest rates, looked reasonable for recovery but export opportunities
were being severely affected by the downturn in the rest of Europe, which
would get worse before it got better.
In the first two months of this year, UK sales of counterbalanced trucks
rose 22 per cent whereas, Mr Lovatt said, sales in Germany and France fell
by 30 per cent and 45 per cent respectively.
Although the present recession has not been as severe as that suffered by
the industry a decade ago, when sales dropped by nearly 50 per cent, it has
lasted longer. The UK now accounts for just 10 per cent of the European
market, compared with 15 per cent at the 1988 peak.
</TEXT>
