<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Call for tougher sanctions on Serbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL mediator Lord Owen said yesterday the world had to show
Bosnia's Serbs that it was determined to ensure a peace plan was implemented
in Bosnia.
He was speaking as UN relief workers used the second day of the ceasefire in
Bosnia to evacuate about 2,140 sick and wounded women, children and elderly
people from Srebrenica, the Moslem enclave in the eastern part of the
republic. Several died on the journey.
The evacuees, jammed into 19 lorries for the eight-hour triop, crossed Serb
lines into Tuzla. At least 45 people in the convoy were critically ill.
In Geneva, yesterday Lord Owen said he hoped the United Nations Security
Council would couple support for the peace plan with proposals for tougher
sanctions against the rump of Yugoslavia, made up of Serbia and Montenegro.
'There is no doubt that if Yugoslavia were to turn off the tap of strategic
supplies. . . the Bosnian Serbs would not be able to sustain the war for too
long,' he said.
Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said the US would intensify
diplomatic pressure on Bosnian Serbs to accept the peace plan and revive its
effort to enforce a Bosnia no-fly zone.
In New York, a deadline of midnight tomorrow for renewing the mandate of the
13,000-strong UN force in the former Yugoslavia added urgency to a new round
of Security Council deliberations.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary general, recommending an extension,
said withdrawing the troops now would probably result in renewed
hostilities.
Nato is planning to send at least 50,000 troops to Bosnia to enforce the
peace plan, but only when all parties have signed. Mr Johan Joergen Holst,
the Norwegian defence minister, said yesterday the figure would probably be
more like 75,000, but that no country had so far committed forces.
Mr William Perry, US deputy defence secretary, told a meeting of defence
ministers from Nato, eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union in Brussels
that Washington might commit ground forces to help make up the total.
Russia, however, indicated it would not be sending significant forces since
it was 'over-extended' with peacekeeping operations in the former Soviet
Union. Nato officials, expressing surprise, said Mr Pavel Grachev, Russian
defence minister, had indicated his country would contribute up to 13,000
men.
Meanwhile, a second convoy, carrying food, plastic sheeting and tents, was
waiting to set out for Srebrenica yesterday, but was delayed.
Srebrenica has been under Serb siege for the past 11 months. Its population
of 9,000 has swelled to nearly 60,000 with refugees from the fighting. Many
have died from starvation or shellfire. Suffering chronic shortages of food
and medicine, aid workers in Srebrenica said the population was desperate to
escape.
Diplomats, who believe Srebrenica is the most vulnerable of the few
remaining enclaves in eastern Bosnia, say that despite US air drops the
situation there is still 'very grave'.
Even so, the Bosnian Serb government yesterday protested for 'deep-rooted
historical reasons' to the UNHCR about the use of German military aircraft
to drop relief supplies over eastern Bosnia. Germany sent its first cargo
aircraft to join the US-led mission on Sunday night.
In Zagreb, the Croatian government resigned, against a background of
increasing economic deprivation. Mr Nikica Valentic, head of Ina, Croatia's
state-owned oil company, was named as prime minister.
</TEXT>
