<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / 'Crucial' talks today in Tyneside shipyard dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT and unions at a Tyneside ship repair company where 350 workers
have been given redundancy notices after rejecting a cost-cutting pay deal
meet today in an attempt to find common ground.
The talks, described by management as 'crucial' and by the unions as 'make
or break', are being held as the workers enter the sixth week of their
12-week notice period.
They have been told that if they want to work for A &amp; P Appledore Tyne
beyond mid-May they must accept new terms of employment. The workers, who
earlier this month staged a one-day unofficial strike, have since voted in a
ballot by four to one for industrial action.
The company, part of A &amp; P Appledore Holdings, says it must cut costs at its
Tyneside repair yards in North Shields and Wallsend because of the world
recession and increasing competition. It says the yards made a loss last
year. 'The very existence of the company is on the line,' it said.
The package rejected by the hourly paid employees includes a pay freeze and
reductions in other payments. The unions are especially opposed to proposals
that temporary workers should be paid lower rates than permanent employees,
and that entitlement to idle-time payments when lack of work results in
layoffs should be reduced from the present maximum of 60 days a year.
Mr David Blincow, managing director of A &amp; P Appledore Tyne, said: 'We have
to get about 10 per cent of costs out of the business.'
</TEXT>
