<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / French Elections: Tide that turned in favour of Noir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the few to have withstood the tide of mainstream conservatism last
night was Mr Michel Noir, mayor of Lyons and former member of the RPR
Gaullist party.
Key to Mr Noir's 58 per cent vote in the run-off was the fact that his
opponent, Mr Alain Merieux, the official RPR candidate, gained the unwelcome
personal endorsement of the National Front candidate eliminated in the first
round a week ago. Mr Merieux thus seemed to have gained fewer votes from the
NF than he lost from left-wing electors who came out to back the mayor in
what they saw as a proxy fight against the NF.
Mr Merieux had come out of the first round on March 18 narrowly ahead of Mr
Noir. He seemed well placed to capitalise after a campaign funding scandal
at the centre of which was the mayor's son-in-law, Mr Pierre Botton. Mr
Botton, a Lyons businessman, is now in jail.
What turned the tide in his favour, Mr Noir claimed last night, was the
sense of independence of the Lyonnais who did not want to see their city's
politics dictated by RPR party HQ in Paris, and Mr Merieux's 'alliance' with
the NF.
Mr Noir was once an RPR minister of trade, but left the party several years
ago to try to form his own local movement.
That failed because 'Noirist' candidates did not win any seats in Lyons. He
said last night he saw himself as a member of the parliament's 'new
majority', but added it was not clear in which group he would sit.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
    P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
