<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / French conservative parties rout the left in election
run-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S centre-right coalition last night swept to victory, leaving the
outgoing Socialists and other leftwing parties with fewer than 100 seats in
the 577-seat National Assembly.
With 569 seats counted, the RPR Gaullists and the centre-right UDF parties
had won 458 seats and the Socialists had only 53. Several ministers of the
outgoing Socialist government lost their seats.
Within the victorious coalition, the Gaullist RPR party had a clear lead in
seats over its UDF partner, making it highly likely that President Francois
Mitterrand will choose the new prime minister from within the RPR's ranks.
The president will today receive the resignation of Socialist prime minister
Pierre Beregovoy, who at least saved his own parliamentary seat. Mr
Mitterrand is in theory free to pick the prime minister of his choice. In
practice, he is likely to have to choose a premier from the party that has
gained most seats.
Mr Jacques Chirac, the RPR leader whose main ambition is to succeed Mr
Mitterrand in the presidency in 1995, indicated that he did not expect to be
the new premier. The new government would have 'all my support', he said. Mr
Chirac's preferred candidate for the premiership is Mr Edouard Balladur, the
RPR finance minister in the conservatives' first cohabitation government
under President Mitterrand.
After the Gaullist lead was confirmed, former president Valery Giscard
d'Estaing, the UDF leader, said: 'I do not see under what circumstances I
would have a role in this (new) government.'
The Socialists were likely to end with fewer than 60 seats, compared with
the 266 which they and their minor allies had held in the last parliament.
The Socialist rout was dramatically underscored by the defeat of Mr Michel
Rocard, who hopes to be the party's standard-bearer in the 1995 presidential
contest, although an opinion poll showed most voters believed he should give
up the race.
Another Socialist heavyweight to fall last night was Mr Roland Dumas, the
foreign minister, who failed to keep his Dordogne seat. He is considered
likely to go to the Elysee Palace as a presidential adviser on foreign
policy, expected to be a contested area in Mr Mitterrand's cohabitation with
the conservatives.
Two of President Mitterrand's Socialist favourites, Mr Bernard Tapie and Mr
Jack Lang, respectively the ministers for cities and for education, kept
their seats.
The turn-out appeared to be no higher than the 68.9 per cent in last week's
first round of voting. The outgoing Socialist government thus failed in its
call on leftwing voters and abstentionists to rally behind it to limit the
size of the centre-right landslide, which in the first round saw 80 seats
going to the conservatives and none to the left.
Under the French parliamentary system, in which 58 votes are needed to
launch censure motions against the government, the Socialists have barely
done well enough to perform as an effective opposition. But they will get
support from the Communists who were assured of retaining at least 23 of
their 25 seats, thanks largely to the heavy geographical concentration of
their supporters. Mr Georges Marchais, the Communist leader, was re-elected.
The extreme rightwing National Front, led by Mr Jean-Marie Le Pen who has
failed to enter parliament, lost its only seat.
Details, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 17
Lex, Page 18
Ian Davidson, Page 32
</TEXT>
