<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / Yeltsin rides the Congress peaks and troughs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Russian Congress of People's Deputies usually refuses to run to a simple
script. It is an inchoate body, made up of shifting factions and allegiances
with many deputies lacking representative experience. But the key to the
ebbs and flows of resolutions, decisions and stalemates of this past weekend
was in the stubborn fact that the deputies lacked the necessary votes to
impeach the president, Mr Boris Yeltsin.
This was despite the fact that after an appearance before the microphones
which frightened his supporters and delighted his opponents because of its
incoherence, he lost that sliver of support which had deprived his foes of
the majority they needed to put the issue on the agenda. To the end, he
seemed able to disappoint them of the two-thirds needed to impeach him.
The congress has registered great waves and troughs in the apparent strength
of the opposing side. On Friday, the president kept firm to his insistence
he hold a referendum of April 25 on trust. He felt strong enough to taunt
the deputies to put the question of trust in themselves on the ballot paper.
The voices from the floor were looking for compromise, following the
defection from the impeachment camp of Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the
parliamentary speaker.
Saturday morning marked the beginning of efforts to find a compromise. A
resolution was put forward by the drafting committee, allowing the
referendum but adding three more questions to the president's original one.
These were: approval for election of president, for election of the deputies
and - the sting in the tail - approval of the results of economic reform,
which the president has consistently supported and which is assumed to be
deeply unpopular. The president's side let if be known this was
unacceptable.
Though they had gathered in the expectation of discussing impeachment, the
issue had not got on the agenda: a vote on Saturday confirmed that the
necessary simple majority to discuss it still did not exist. Nor was the
resolution on a four-question referendum allowed. Later, a harder line
resolution appeared, proposing to suspend those of the president's aides who
had persuaded him to appeal to the people on March 20, cancel his special
powers, and dismiss his appointed provincial governors.
Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, prime minister, took the stage in the morning
session to give a speech of heavily-qualified support for his president, in
which he was careful to say that 'without the president we will not be able
to carry the heavy burden (of reforms)'. But it was also a speech which
inserted the views that all sides were equally guilty for the crisis which
had brought Russia 'to the brink of catastrophe'.
It made the point that a decree issued by Mr Yeltsin early last week
dismissing the chief administrators of Novosibirsk and Irkutsk had had to be
revoked (Mr Chernomyrdin, rather pointedly, had made fulsome apologies to
them for his president's mistake); and that early elections, which Mr
Yeltsin has not favoured, were inevitable. In the general debate, the most
cheered speaker was Mr Aman Tuleev, head of the Kemerovo region, who branded
Mr Yeltsin's much-abused aides as a 'collective Rasputin'. But pro-Yeltsin
deputies took the floor to defend economic reform and charge the Congress
with unconstitutional behaviour.
Mr Yeltsin's appearance before the microphones most harmed him. His face
puffy, his hair flopping, he came to the microphone and with slurred diction
and long pauses, said there should be a week of talks between himself, Mr
Khasbulatov and Mr Chernomyrdin to try to find consensus.
A number of his opponents said he was drunk; his supporters said he was
over-strained; his staff that he was suffering from the effects of his
mother's death last week, an explanation he later proffered himself in
remarks to reporters.
Yesterday morning, another consensus rabbit appeared from the
behind-the-scenes hat. Said to have the support of the president, the
speaker, the prime minister, the leaders of regions and republics and
'several factions', this resolution scrapped the referendum in favour of
November elections to a two-tier parliament (which meant the scrapping of
the present Congress).
Mr Yeltsin, looking a little better, said that were it to be supported, he
would cancel his decree calling for a popular vote on April 25. There
followed some dozen speakers, each of whom denounced the draft agreement: if
any faction really had put their name to it overnight, none admitted it in
the hall. It went down with a mere 134 votes in favour.
A feature of the rhetoric on this issue was an increase in the calls for the
resignation of the Speaker, a move brewing since the beginning of the
Congress, but which now took off. The nimbleness of Mr Khasbulatov's
footwork was now turned against him: he was represented as a man of no
principle.
The proposal to vote on the impeachment of the president was finally put on
the agenda, with 594 deputies voting for its inclusion. At the same time,
slightly more deputies (614) voted to ballot on a no-confidence motion on Mr
Khasbulatov. Mr Yeltsin's vote required two-thirds of the total number, that
is, 689 out of 1,033: Mr Khasbulatov's majority was a mere 517.
</TEXT>
<XX>
