<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / Heseltine fails to calm Tory fears on pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of a Tory revolt today over pit closures was re-emerging last
night as Mr Michael Heseltine failed to calm the fears of some Conservatives
that the 12 reprieved pits may not survive more than a year.
The trade and industry secretary shrugged off concern among a growing number
of Tory MPs that British Coal might scupper the hopes raised by his coal
rescue package. He said 'dramatic opportunities' had been given to the
industry via government subsidies worth Pounds 300m to Pounds 400m.
A hint from British Coal executives that further pit closures were
inevitable around April next year was, 'one hypothetical doom-laden
scenario', Mr Heseltine said on BBC television yesterday. But he admitted he
could not 'sign up in blood' to a guarantee that pits would stay open, and
indicated government subsidies would last only two years, until
privatisation.
There was comfort for Mr Heseltine, however, when it emerged the electricity
and coal industries had finally reached agreement on contracts through which
the UK's power companies would buy 160m tonnes of coal from British Coal in
the next five years. Signings are expected to be completed today.
This will secure a future for the 19 pits which British Coal considers its
best and will clear the way for talks on additional contracts aimed at
providing a lifeline for another 19 which last week were told they would
either be reprieved, mothballed or developed without being mined.
The contracts, which they have started signing after months of wrangling
within the coal and electricity industries, are worth Pounds 5.5bn to
British Coal.
In parliament, government business managers are braced for a possible
anti-government vote by at least two Conservative MPs. Another six or more
might abstain. A trade union lobby of parliament will increase the pressure
on wavering Tories but the government was last night confident of winning
the vote.
Defeat would require 11 Tories to vote against the government, if all the
other political parties were opposed to the package. The Ulster Unionists
could decide to abstain, however, making defeat still less likely.
In a move timed to help the vote, Mr Peter Lilley, social security
secretary, will today announce extra help for former miners suffering from
chronic bronchitis and emphysema, implementing recommendations last November
by the Industrial Injuries Advisory Committee.
Industry disablement benefit will be available to those suffers who have
worked more than 20 years underground.
Potential Tory rebels meet this morning to discuss tactics. The most
vociferous yesterday, Mr Winston Churchill, said he was 'looking for very
specific assurances by the chairman of British Coal' about the future of the
12 reprieved pits. Without them, 'the government would need to be very
worried about its majority', he said.
