FT  29 MAR 93 / Troubled Scots pit restarts production
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONKTONHALL, the Edinburgh colliery leased from British Coal by a miners'
consortium, was due to resume production last night after losing two days'
output after the death of a miner on Saturday.
The accident at the coalface was a further setback to the pit which is in
serious financial difficulties. On Friday the 160 miners received their
first week's pay for after working without pay for eight weeks.
The miner, Mr William Gorman, 35, was killed when part of the roof collapsed
at the colliery's only coalface. He had joined the Monktonhall Mineworkers
consortium nine weeks ago by subscribing Pounds 10,000 to buy his stake in
the company.
An inspector from the mines inspectorate of the government's Health and
Safety Executive is investigating the accident, the first since the mine was
reopened last summer.
The consortium has debts of more than Pounds 1.6m and Bank of Scotland has
refused to advance more cash.
At the end of last month the consortium appealed for a partner to inject new
capital to keep going but later turned down an offer from Caledonian Mining,
an English company which wanted to take a controlling stake.
Although Monktonhall has orders from British Coal and ScottishPower, it
incurred debts because of a three-month delay in resuming production at the
pit at the end of 1992.
