<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / Ethnic groups' disparity widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN increasing disparity is emerging between the circumstances of ethnic
minority groups, the Policy Studies Institute says today.
Its research, based on a study of the Department of Employment's labour
force survey, says a complex pattern now exists which 'can no longer be
adequately summarised by a simple contrast between relatively well-off
'whites' and poorly-off 'blacks'.'
The report says that members of the African-Asian and Indian communities
have higher proportions of well-qualified people, have attained comparable
job status with whites, and have unemployment rates closest to those of the
majority population. At the opposite end of the spectrum, Pakistanis and
Bangladeshis have the largest proportions of people without formal
qualifications and consistently suffer the highest jobless rates.
Afro-Caribbean people tended to be in a more complex position between these
two extremes. But, concludes the report, it was clear that general
circumstances had changed little for people of Afro-Caribbean, Pakistani and
Bangladeshi origin over the past 10 years. They remained concentrated in
lower-level jobs, and were subject to much higher rates of unemployment than
other ethnic groups.
Research suggested that levels of racial discrimination in the mid 1980s
were similar to those of the mid 1970s, it says.
Britain's Ethnic Minorities. BEBC Distribution, PO Box 1496, Poole, Dorset,
BH12 3YD Pounds 15
Monday interview, Page 32
</TEXT>
