<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / Sex-case tribunals may curb publicity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIAL TRIBUNALS are to be given the power to restrict press reporting
of sexual harassment cases, following a late government amendment to the
employment bill, which is going through the House of Lords.
The amendment, due to be tabled today, is certain to be accepted. It will
prevent either alleged victims or alleged harassers from being identified
while a case is being heard. The measure could also be extended to
protecting witnesses.
The Equal Opportunities Commission has been arguing for some time that many
women are put off from bringing harassment cases because of what is seen as
sensationalised reporting by the tabloid press of the evidence. It knows of
cases where women have received hate mail and have even been attacked after
their addresses have been published.
Any reporting restrictions imposed will last only until a tribunal reaches
its final judgment, unless the case involves allegations of indecent assault
or rape, when protection for the alleged victim would last for life.
Judge Timothy Lawrence, president of the industrial tribunals in England and
Wales, wrote to the government last year to express his concern about the
lack of protection for sexual harassment cases. Other bodies, including
community law centres, have also put forward evidence of distress and
embarrassment caused by the reporting of tribunals.
Hammersmith and Fulham Community Law Centre in London wrote to the
Department of Employment: 'It is our experience that many clients simply do
not make applications to the industrial tribunal because of their anxiety
about the hearing.
'In many of the cases that we deal with, the woman has never spoken about
her experiences before, and even discussing the harassment in private
presents difficulties . . . It is our view that any steps which could be
taken to increase the privacy of the hearing would encourage applicants to
proceed with their claims.'
</TEXT>
