<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / Managers' pay rises slow but beat inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS' basic pay comfortably outstripped inflation in the 12 months to
February but the trend of the settlements fell in the course of the year, a
survey of more than 1,000 companies has found.
The survey by pay research group Reward found that basic pay rose by 4.4 per
cent in the year, compared with a 1.8 per cent rise in the retail prices
index, but that six months ago pay was rising at an annual rate of more than
5.5 per cent.
Another survey published today also shows that average pay increases are
falling but are still more than double the rate of inflation.
Increases averaged 4.2 per cent in the quarter to the start of January, the
latest Hay Compensation report says.
However, the quarterly study of pay awards among 573 large and medium-sized
UK organisations covering 188,000 jobs in the management and clerical
sectors says deals averaged 6 per cent in the same period of the previous
year. The downward trend is further reflected in the annual figures, which
averaged 5.6 per cent over the 12 months to the beginning of January
compared with 9 per cent in 1991.
Mr Steve Flather, Reward managing director, said that pay rises were
responding to the drop in inflation. 'But these results also suggest that
those organisations which are surviving the tough times of the recession are
giving above-inflation increases to ensure that they retain their key
staff,' he said.
Few managers have swapped their company cars for cash, Reward found. Indeed,
with the exception of senior managers, the percentage of managers with cars
has risen slightly. Among senior managers, 81.6 per cent now receive cars,
compared with 82.3 per cent in March 1992. The figure for middle managers
has risen from 37.9 per cent in 1992 to 39.6 per cent. Among junior
managers, 20.2 per cent have cars, compared with 19.8 per cent last year.
Last year's graduate recruits earn a little more than the current batch of
entrants to the jobs market, according to Reward. The average graduate
starting salary is Pounds 12,750, with a range of Pounds 11,720 to Pounds
14,000. Last year's graduates have an average salary of Pounds 12,800, with
a range of Pounds 11,750 to Pounds 14,000.
The Hay study found that average pay increases in the latest quarter were
highest for top management at 5.6 per cent (5.9 per cent for the year) and
lowest for middle management at 3.6 per cent (5.7 per cent for the year).
Clerical staff averaged 4.2 per cent for the quarter but recorded the lowest
annual average increase at 5.4 per cent.
The Hay study expects average salary increases to remain at about 4 per cent
over the next 12 months, although top management is expected to receive
average increases of 4.7 per cent.
Reward management survey, Diamond Way, Stone Business Park, Stone,
Staffordshire ST15 OSD. Pounds 200. Hay Compensation Report, 25 Wellington
Street, Covent Garden, London WC2E 7DA.
</TEXT>
