<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 93 / News Corp seeks Dollars 3bn and The Post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RUPERT Murdoch's News Corporation is seeking a Dollars 3bn (Pounds
2.10bn) revolving loan from a group of 30 to 40 international banks to help
refinance outstanding debts at lower interest rates.
Although terms of the deal, believed to have a maturity of more than five
years, were not available, it is understood that Citibank of the US and
Midland of the UK are among the lead banks involved.
The Dollars 3bn refinancing is the latest step in the restructuring of News
Corp's debt. In late 1990, News Corp was facing severe financial problems
with debts of more than Dollars 7.6bn. News Corp was forced into lengthy
negotiations with nearly 150 lending banks and after months of talks, it was
agreed that about Dollars 7.6bn of debt would be restructured over three
years.
Separately, Mr Murdoch announced last night that he had signed an agreement
with Mr Abe Hirschfeld, a New York car parks magnate, to transfer control of
The New York Post, the bankrupt tabloid newspaper, to News Corp.
The accord will depend upon the outcome of a joint application to be made
this morning by the two before a New York bankruptcy judge. The deal was
signed yesterday by Mr Murdoch, who lost an estimated Dollars 150m when he
last owned the newspaper in 1988, following a meeting on Friday evening with
Mr Hirschfeld, who has controlled The Post since March 12.
The offer will involve Mr Murdoch providing operating capital and taking
control of the paper for the next 60 days, pending the approval from the
Federal Communications Commission (FCC) of a request to waive rules that
normally prevent cross-ownership of both a newspaper and a television
station in one city.
If today's hearing goes well Mr Murdoch could obtain operating control of
the newspaper from as early as tonight. . He already has the support of Mr
Mario Cuomo, the New York governor, as well as the paper's editorial staff,
creditors and managers - many of whom have been horrified at the behaviour
of Mr Hirschfeld.
Mr Murdoch's costs over the next 60 days may reach Dollars 8m and he would
then have to provide a plan to bring The Post out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection.
'Although we are hopeful that we can successfully conclude these
arrangements there remain very serious obstacles,' Mr Murdoch said last
night.
</TEXT>
<XX>
